153// Internal Assertions and errors
154#if !defined(ELPP_DISABLE_ASSERT)
155# if (defined(ELPP_DEBUG_ASSERT_FAILURE))
156# define ELPP_ASSERT(expr, msg) if (!(expr)) { std
157 ::stringstream internalInfoStream; internalInfoStream << msg; ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR
158 \
159<<"EASYLOGGING++ ASSERTION FAILED (LINE: " << __LINE__ << ") [" #expr << "] WITH MESSAGE \"" \
160<<ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_MSG(internalInfoStream.str()) << "\"" << ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_ENDL; base::utils::abort(1, \
161"ELPP Assertion failure, please define ELPP_DEBUG_ASSERT_FAILURE");}
162# else
163# define ELPP_ASSERT(expr, msg) if (!(expr)) { std
164 ::stringstream internalInfoStream; internalInfoStream << msg; ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR
165 \
166<<"ASSERTION FAILURE FROM EASYLOGGING++ (LINE: " \
167<<__LINE__ << ") [" #expr << "] WITH MESSAGE \"" << ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_MSG(internalInfoStream.str()) << "\"" \
168<<ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_ENDL; }
169# endif // (defined(ELPP_DEBUG_ASSERT_FAILURE))
170#else
171# define ELPP_ASSERT(x, y)
172#endif //(!defined(ELPP_DISABLE_ASSERT)
173#if ELPP_COMPILER_MSVC
174# define ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_WRITE_PERROR \
175{char buff[256]; strerror_s(buff, 256, errno); ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR
176 << ": " << buff << " [" << errno << "]";} (void)0
177#else
178# define ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_WRITE_PERROR ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR
179 << ": " << strerror(errno) << " [" << errno << "]"; (void)0
180#endif // ELPP_COMPILER_MSVC
181#if defined(ELPP_DEBUG_ERRORS)
182# if !defined(ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR)
183# define ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR(msg, pe) { std
184 ::stringstream internalInfoStream; internalInfoStream << "<ERROR> " << msg; ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR
185 \
186<<"ERROR FROM EASYLOGGING++ (LINE: " << __LINE__ << ") " \
187<<ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_MSG(internalInfoStream.str()) << ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_ENDL; if
188 (pe) { ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_ERROR << " "; ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_WRITE_PERROR; }} (void)0
189# endif
190#else
191# undef ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO
192# define ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR(msg, pe)
193#endif // defined(ELPP_DEBUG_ERRORS)
194#if (defined(ELPP_DEBUG_INFO))
195# if !(defined(ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO_LEVEL))
196# define ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO_LEVEL 9
197# endif // !(defined(ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO_LEVEL))
198# if !defined(ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO)
199# define ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO(lvl, msg) { if (lvl <= ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO_LEVEL) { std
200 ::stringstream internalInfoStream; internalInfoStream << "<INFO> " << msg; ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_OUT_INFO
201 << ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_MSG(internalInfoStream.str()) \
202<<ELPP_INTERNAL_DEBUGGING_ENDL; }}
203# endif
204#else

548/// @brief Internal helper class that prevent copy constructor for class
549///
550/// @detail When using this class simply inherit it privately
551class NoCopy {
552 protected:
553 NoCopy(void) {}
554 private:
555 NoCopy(const NoCopy&);
556 NoCopy& operator=(const NoCopy&);
557};
558/// @brief Internal helper class that makes all default constructors private.
559///
560/// @detail This prevents initializing class making it static unless an explicit constructor is declared.
561/// When using this class simply inherit it privately
562class StaticClass {
563 private:
564 StaticClass(void);
565 StaticClass(const StaticClass&);
566 StaticClass& operator=(const StaticClass&);
567};
568} // namespace base
569/// @brief Represents enumeration for severity level used to determine level of logging
570///
571/// @detail With Easylogging++, developers may disable or enable any level regardless of
572/// what the severity is. Or they can choose to log using hierarchical logging flag
573enum class Level : base::type::EnumType {
574 /// @brief Generic level that represents all the levels. Useful when setting global configuration for all levels
575 Global = 1,
576 /// @brief Information that can be useful to back-trace certain events - mostly useful than debug logs.
577 Trace = 2,
578 /// @brief Informational events most useful for developers to debug application
579 Debug = 4,
580 /// @brief Severe error information that will presumably abort application
581 Fatal = 8,
582 /// @brief Information representing errors in application but application will keep running
583 Error = 16,
584 /// @brief Useful when application has potentially harmful situations
585 Warning = 32,
586 /// @brief Information that can be highly useful and vary with verbose logging level.
587 Verbose = 64,
588 /// @brief Mainly useful to represent current progress of application
589 Info = 128,
590 /// @brief Represents unknown level
591 Unknown = 1010
592};
593} // namespace el
594namespace std {
595template<> struct hash<el::Level> {
596 public:
597 std::size_t operator()(const el::Level& l) const {
598 return hash<el::base::type::EnumType> {}(static_cast<el::base::type::EnumType>(l));
599 }
600};
601}
602namespace el {
603/// @brief Static class that contains helper functions for el::Level
604class LevelHelper : base::StaticClass {
605 public:
606 /// @brief Represents minimum valid level. Useful when iterating through enum.
607 static const base::type::EnumType kMinValid = static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(Level::Trace);
608 /// @brief Represents maximum valid level. This is used internally and you should not need it.
609 static const base::type::EnumType kMaxValid = static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(Level::Info);
610 /// @brief Casts level to int, useful for iterating through enum.
611 static base::type::EnumType castToInt(Level level) {
612 return static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(level);
613 }
614 /// @brief Casts int(ushort) to level, useful for iterating through enum.
615 static Level castFromInt(base::type::EnumType l) {
616 return static_cast<Level>(l);
617 }
618 /// @brief Converts level to associated const char*
619 /// @return Upper case string based level.
620 static const char* convertToString(Level level);
621 /// @brief Converts from levelStr to Level
622 /// @param levelStr Upper case string based level.
623 /// Lower case is also valid but providing upper case is recommended.
624 static Level convertFromString(const char* levelStr);
625 /// @brief Applies specified function to each level starting from startIndex
626 /// @param startIndex initial value to start the iteration from. This is passed as pointer and
627 /// is left-shifted so this can be used inside function (fn) to represent current level.
628 /// @param fn function to apply with each level. This bool represent whether or not to stop iterating through levels.
629 static void forEachLevel(base::type::EnumType* startIndex, const std::function<bool(void)>& fn);
630};
631/// @brief Represents enumeration of ConfigurationType used to configure or access certain aspect
632/// of logging
633enum class ConfigurationType : base::type::EnumType {
634 /// @brief Determines whether or not corresponding level and logger of logging is enabled
635 /// You may disable all logs by using el::Level::Global
636 Enabled = 1,
637 /// @brief Whether or not to write corresponding log to log file
638 ToFile = 2,
639 /// @brief Whether or not to write corresponding level and logger log to standard output.
640 /// By standard output meaning termnal, command prompt etc
641 ToStandardOutput = 4,
642 /// @brief Determines format of logging corresponding level and logger.
643 Format = 8,
644 /// @brief Determines log file (full path) to write logs to for corresponding level and logger
645 Filename = 16,
646 /// @brief Specifies precision of the subsecond part. It should be within range (1-6).
647 SubsecondPrecision = 32,
648 /// @brief Alias of SubsecondPrecision (for backward compatibility)
649 MillisecondsWidth = SubsecondPrecision,
650 /// @brief Determines whether or not performance tracking is enabled.
651 ///
652 /// @detail This does not depend on logger or level. Performance tracking always uses 'performance' logger
653 PerformanceTracking = 64,
654 /// @brief Specifies log file max size.
655 ///
656 /// @detail If file size of corresponding log file (for corresponding level) is >= specified size, log file will
657 /// be truncated and re-initiated.
658 MaxLogFileSize = 128,
659 /// @brief Specifies number of log entries to hold until we flush pending log data
660 LogFlushThreshold = 256,
661 /// @brief Represents unknown configuration
662 Unknown = 1010
663};
664/// @brief Static class that contains helper functions for el::ConfigurationType
665class ConfigurationTypeHelper : base::StaticClass {
666 public:
667 /// @brief Represents minimum valid configuration type. Useful when iterating through enum.
668 static const base::type::EnumType kMinValid = static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(ConfigurationType::Enabled);
669 /// @brief Represents maximum valid configuration type. This is used internally and you should not need it.
670 static const base::type::EnumType kMaxValid = static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(ConfigurationType::MaxLogFileSize);
671 /// @brief Casts configuration type to int, useful for iterating through enum.
672 static base::type::EnumType castToInt(ConfigurationType configurationType) {
673 return static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(configurationType);
674 }
675 /// @brief Casts int(ushort) to configuration type, useful for iterating through enum.
676 static ConfigurationType castFromInt(base::type::EnumType c) {
677 return static_cast<ConfigurationType>(c);
678 }
679 /// @brief Converts configuration type to associated const char*
680 /// @returns Upper case string based configuration type.
681 static const char* convertToString(ConfigurationType configurationType);
682 /// @brief Converts from configStr to ConfigurationType
683 /// @param configStr Upper case string based configuration type.
684 /// Lower case is also valid but providing upper case is recommended.
685 static ConfigurationType convertFromString(const char* configStr);
686 /// @brief Applies specified function to each configuration type starting from startIndex
687 /// @param startIndex initial value to start the iteration from. This is passed by pointer and is left-shifted
688 /// so this can be used inside function (fn) to represent current configuration type.
689 /// @param fn function to apply with each configuration type.
690 /// This bool represent whether or not to stop iterating through configurations.
691 static inline void forEachConfigType(base::type::EnumType* startIndex, const std::function<bool(void)>& fn);
692};
693/// @brief Flags used while writing logs. This flags are set by user
694enum class LoggingFlag : base::type::EnumType {
695 /// @brief Makes sure we have new line for each container log entry
696 NewLineForContainer = 1,
697 /// @brief Makes sure if -vmodule is used and does not specifies a module, then verbose
698 /// logging is allowed via that module.
699 AllowVerboseIfModuleNotSpecified = 2,
700 /// @brief When handling crashes by default, detailed crash reason will be logged as well
701 LogDetailedCrashReason = 4,
702 /// @brief Allows to disable application abortion when logged using FATAL level
703 DisableApplicationAbortOnFatalLog = 8,
704 /// @brief Flushes log with every log-entry (performance sensitive) - Disabled by default
705 ImmediateFlush = 16,
706 /// @brief Enables strict file rolling
707 StrictLogFileSizeCheck = 32,
708 /// @brief Make terminal output colorful for supported terminals
709 ColoredTerminalOutput = 64,
710 /// @brief Supports use of multiple logging in same macro, e.g, CLOG(INFO, "default", "network")
711 MultiLoggerSupport = 128,
712 /// @brief Disables comparing performance tracker's checkpoints
713 DisablePerformanceTrackingCheckpointComparison = 256,
714 /// @brief Disable VModules
715 DisableVModules = 512,
716 /// @brief Disable VModules extensions
717 DisableVModulesExtensions = 1024,
718 /// @brief Enables hierarchical logging
719 HierarchicalLogging = 2048,
720 /// @brief Creates logger automatically when not available
721 CreateLoggerAutomatically = 4096,
722 /// @brief Adds spaces b/w logs that separated by left-shift operator
723 AutoSpacing = 8192,
724 /// @brief Preserves time format and does not convert it to sec, hour etc (performance tracking only)
725 FixedTimeFormat = 16384,
726 // @brief Ignore SIGINT or crash
727 IgnoreSigInt = 32768,
728};

833/// @brief A subsecond precision class containing actual width and offset of the subsecond part
834class SubsecondPrecision {
835 public:
836 SubsecondPrecision(void) {
837 init(base::consts::kDefaultSubsecondPrecision);
838 }
839 explicit SubsecondPrecision(int width) {
840 init(width);
841 }
842 bool operator==(const SubsecondPrecision& ssPrec) {
843 return m_width == ssPrec.m_width && m_offset == ssPrec.m_offset;
844 }
845 int m_width;
846 unsigned int m_offset;
847 private:
848 void init(int width);
849};
850/// @brief Type alias of SubsecondPrecision
851typedef SubsecondPrecision MillisecondsWidth;
852/// @brief Namespace containing utility functions/static classes used internally
853namespace utils {
854/// @brief Deletes memory safely and points to null
855template <typename T>
856static
857typename std::enable_if<std::is_pointer<T*>::value, void>::type
858safeDelete(T*& pointer) {
859 if (pointer == nullptr)
860 return;
861 delete pointer;
862 pointer = nullptr;
863}
864/// @brief Bitwise operations for C++11 strong enum class. This casts e into Flag_T and returns value after bitwise operation
865/// Use these function as <pre>flag = bitwise::Or<MyEnum>(MyEnum::val1, flag);</pre>
866namespace bitwise {
867template <typename Enum>
868static inline base::type::EnumType And(Enum e, base::type::EnumType flag) {
869 return static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(flag) & static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(e);
870}
871template <typename Enum>
872static inline base::type::EnumType Not(Enum e, base::type::EnumType flag) {
873 return static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(flag) & ~(static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(e));
874}
875template <typename Enum>
876static inline base::type::EnumType Or(Enum e, base::type::EnumType flag) {
877 return static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(flag) | static_cast<base::type::EnumType>(e);
878}
879} // namespace bitwise
880template <typename Enum>
881static inline void addFlag(Enum e, base::type::EnumType* flag) {
882 *flag = base::utils::bitwise::Or<Enum>(e, *flag);
883}
884template <typename Enum>
885static inline void removeFlag(Enum e, base::type::EnumType* flag) {
886 *flag = base::utils::bitwise::Not<Enum>(e, *flag);
887}
888template <typename Enum>
889static inline bool hasFlag(Enum e, base::type::EnumType flag) {
890 return base::utils::bitwise::And<Enum>(e, flag) > 0x0;
891}
892} // namespace utils
893namespace threading {
894#if ELPP_THREADING_ENABLED
895# if !ELPP_USE_STD_THREADING
896namespace internal {
897/// @brief A mutex wrapper for compiler that dont yet support std::recursive_mutex
898class Mutex : base::NoCopy {
899 public:
900 Mutex(void) {
901# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
902 pthread_mutexattr_t attr;
903 pthread_mutexattr_init(&attr);
904 pthread_mutexattr_settype(&attr, PTHREAD_MUTEX_RECURSIVE);
905 pthread_mutex_init(&m_underlyingMutex, &attr);
906 pthread_mutexattr_destroy(&attr);
907# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
908 InitializeCriticalSection(&m_underlyingMutex);
909# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
910 }
911
912 virtual ~Mutex(void) {
913# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
914 pthread_mutex_destroy(&m_underlyingMutex);
915# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
916 DeleteCriticalSection(&m_underlyingMutex);
917# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
918 }
919
920 inline void lock(void) {
921# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
922 pthread_mutex_lock(&m_underlyingMutex);
923# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
924 EnterCriticalSection(&m_underlyingMutex);
925# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
926 }
927
928 inline bool try_lock(void) {
929# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
930 return (pthread_mutex_trylock(&m_underlyingMutex) == 0);
931# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
932 return TryEnterCriticalSection(&m_underlyingMutex);
933# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
934 }
935
936 inline void unlock(void) {
937# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
938 pthread_mutex_unlock(&m_underlyingMutex);
939# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
940 LeaveCriticalSection(&m_underlyingMutex);
941# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
942 }
943
944 private:
945# if ELPP_OS_UNIX
946 pthread_mutex_t m_underlyingMutex;
947# elif ELPP_OS_WINDOWS
948 CRITICAL_SECTION m_underlyingMutex;
949# endif // ELPP_OS_UNIX
950};
951/// @brief Scoped lock for compiler that dont yet support std::lock_guard
952template <typename M>
953class ScopedLock : base::NoCopy {
954 public:
955 explicit ScopedLock(M& mutex) {
956 m_mutex = &mutex;
957 m_mutex->lock();
958 }
959
960 virtual ~ScopedLock(void) {
961 m_mutex->unlock();
962 }
963 private:
964 M* m_mutex;
965 ScopedLock(void);
966};
967} // namespace internal
968typedef base::threading::internal::Mutex Mutex;
969typedef base::threading::internal::ScopedLock<base::threading::Mutex> ScopedLock;
970# else
971typedef std::recursive_mutex Mutex;
972typedef std::lock_guard<base::threading::Mutex> ScopedLock;
973# endif // !ELPP_USE_STD_THREADING
974#else
975namespace internal {
976/// @brief Mutex wrapper used when multi-threading is disabled.
977class NoMutex : base::NoCopy {
978 public:
979 NoMutex(void) {}
980 inline void lock(void) {}
981 inline bool try_lock(void) {
982 return true;
983 }
984 inline void unlock(void) {}
985};
986/// @brief Lock guard wrapper used when multi-threading is disabled.
987template <typename Mutex>
988class NoScopedLock : base::NoCopy {
989 public:
990 explicit NoScopedLock(Mutex&) {
991 }
992 virtual ~NoScopedLock(void) {
993 }
994 private:
995 NoScopedLock(void);
996};
997} // namespace internal
998typedef base::threading::internal::NoMutex Mutex;
999typedef base::threading::internal::NoScopedLock<base::threading::Mutex> ScopedLock;
1000#endif // ELPP_THREADING_ENABLED
1001/// @brief Base of thread safe class, this class is inheritable-only
1002class ThreadSafe {
1003 public:
1004 virtual inline void acquireLock(void) ELPP_FINAL { m_mutex.lock(); }
1005 virtual inline void releaseLock(void) ELPP_FINAL { m_mutex.unlock(); }
1006 virtual inline base::threading::Mutex& lock(void) ELPP_FINAL { return m_mutex; }
1007 protected:
1008 ThreadSafe(void) {}
1009 virtual ~ThreadSafe(void) {}
1010 private:
1011 base::threading::Mutex m_mutex;
1012};
1013
1014#if ELPP_THREADING_ENABLED
1015# if !ELPP_USE_STD_THREADING
1016/// @brief Gets ID of currently running threading in windows systems. On unix, nothing is returned.
1017static std::string getCurrentThreadId(void) {
1018 std::stringstream ss;
1019# if (ELPP_OS_WINDOWS)
1020 ss << GetCurrentThreadId();
1021# endif // (ELPP_OS_WINDOWS)
1022 return ss.str();
1023}
1024# else
1025/// @brief Gets ID of currently running threading using std::this_thread::get_id()
1026static std::string getCurrentThreadId(void) {
1027 std::stringstream ss;
1028 ss << std::this_thread::get_id();
1029 return ss.str();
1030}
1031# endif // !ELPP_USE_STD_THREADING
1032#else
1033static inline std::string getCurrentThreadId(void) {
1034 return std::string();
1035}
1036#endif // ELPP_THREADING_ENABLED
1037} // namespace threading

1178/// @brief Contains utilities for cross-platform date/time. This class make use of el::base::utils::Str
1179class DateTime : base::StaticClass {
1180 public:
1181 /// @brief Cross platform gettimeofday for Windows and unix platform. This can be used to determine current microsecond.
1182 ///
1183 /// @detail For unix system it uses gettimeofday(timeval*, timezone*) and for Windows, a separate implementation is provided
1184 /// @param [in,out] tv Pointer that gets updated
1185 static void gettimeofday(struct timeval* tv);
1186
1187 /// @brief Gets current date and time with a subsecond part.
1188 /// @param format User provided date/time format
1189 /// @param ssPrec A pointer to base::SubsecondPrecision from configuration (non-null)
1190 /// @returns string based date time in specified format.
1191 static std::string getDateTime(const char* format, const base::SubsecondPrecision* ssPrec);
1192
1193 /// @brief Converts timeval (struct from ctime) to string using specified format and subsecond precision
1194 static std::string timevalToString(struct timeval tval, const char* format,
1195 const el::base::SubsecondPrecision* ssPrec);
1196
1197 /// @brief Formats time to get unit accordingly, units like second if > 1000 or minutes if > 60000 etc
1198 static base::type::string_t formatTime(unsigned long long time, base::TimestampUnit timestampUnit);
1199
1200 /// @brief Gets time difference in milli/micro second depending on timestampUnit
1201 static unsigned long long getTimeDifference(const struct timeval& endTime, const struct timeval& startTime,
1202 base::TimestampUnit timestampUnit);
1203
1204
1205 static struct ::tm* buildTimeInfo(struct timeval* currTime, struct ::tm* timeInfo);
1206 private:
1207 static char* parseFormat(char* buf, std::size_t bufSz, const char* format, const struct tm* tInfo,
1208 std::size_t msec, const base::SubsecondPrecision* ssPrec);
1209};
1210/// @brief Command line arguments for application if specified using el::Helpers::setArgs(..) or START_EASYLOGGINGPP(..)

1220 setArgs(argc, argv);
1221 }

1231 /// @brief Returns value of arguments

1236 /// @brief Returns true if no params available. This exclude argv[0]

1238 /// @brief Returns total number of arguments. This exclude argv[0]

1241

1244 char** m_argv;

1247};
1248/// @brief Abstract registry (aka repository) that provides basic interface for pointer repository specified by T_Ptr type.
1249///
1250/// @detail Most of the functions are virtual final methods but anything implementing this abstract class should implement
1251/// unregisterAll() and deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>&) and write registerNew() method according to container
1252/// and few more methods; get() to find element, unregister() to unregister single entry.
1253/// Please note that this is thread-unsafe and should also implement thread-safety mechanisms in implementation.
1254template <typename T_Ptr, typename Container>
1255class AbstractRegistry : public base::threading::ThreadSafe {
1256 public:
1257 typedef typename Container::iterator iterator;
1258 typedef typename Container::const_iterator const_iterator;
1259
1260 /// @brief Default constructor
1261 AbstractRegistry(void) {}
1262
1263 /// @brief Move constructor that is useful for base classes
1264 AbstractRegistry(AbstractRegistry&& sr) {
1265 if (this == &sr) {
1266 return;
1267 }
1268 unregisterAll();
1269 m_list = std::move(sr.m_list);
1270 }
1271
1272 bool operator==(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>& other) {
1273 if (size() != other.size()) {
1274 return false;
1275 }
1276 for (std::size_t i = 0; i < m_list.size(); ++i) {
1277 if (m_list.at(i) != other.m_list.at(i)) {
1278 return false;
1279 }
1280 }
1281 return true;
1282 }
1283
1284 bool operator!=(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>& other) {
1285 if (size() != other.size()) {
1286 return true;
1287 }
1288 for (std::size_t i = 0; i < m_list.size(); ++i) {
1289 if (m_list.at(i) != other.m_list.at(i)) {
1290 return true;
1291 }
1292 }
1293 return false;
1294 }
1295
1296 /// @brief Assignment move operator
1297 AbstractRegistry& operator=(AbstractRegistry&& sr) {
1298 if (this == &sr) {
1299 return *this;
1300 }
1301 unregisterAll();
1302 m_list = std::move(sr.m_list);
1303 return *this;
1304 }
1305
1306 virtual ~AbstractRegistry(void) {
1307 }
1308
1309 /// @return Iterator pointer from start of repository
1310 virtual inline iterator begin(void) ELPP_FINAL {
1311 return m_list.begin();
1312 }
1313
1314 /// @return Iterator pointer from end of repository
1315 virtual inline iterator end(void) ELPP_FINAL {
1316 return m_list.end();
1317 }
1318
1319
1320 /// @return Constant iterator pointer from start of repository
1321 virtual inline const_iterator cbegin(void) const ELPP_FINAL {
1322 return m_list.cbegin();
1323 }
1324
1325 /// @return End of repository
1326 virtual inline const_iterator cend(void) const ELPP_FINAL {
1327 return m_list.cend();
1328 }
1329
1330 /// @return Whether or not repository is empty
1331 virtual inline bool empty(void) const ELPP_FINAL {
1332 return m_list.empty();
1333 }
1334
1335 /// @return Size of repository
1336 virtual inline std::size_t size(void) const ELPP_FINAL {
1337 return m_list.size();
1338 }
1339
1340 /// @brief Returns underlying container by reference
1341 virtual inline Container& list(void) ELPP_FINAL {
1342 return m_list;
1343 }
1344
1345 /// @brief Returns underlying container by constant reference.
1346 virtual inline const Container& list(void) const ELPP_FINAL {
1347 return m_list;
1348 }
1349
1350 /// @brief Unregisters all the pointers from current repository.
1351 virtual void unregisterAll(void) = 0;
1352
1353 protected:
1354 virtual void deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>&) = 0;
1355 void reinitDeepCopy(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>& sr) {
1356 unregisterAll();
1357 deepCopy(sr);
1358 }
1359
1360 private:
1361 Container m_list;
1362};
1363
1364/// @brief A pointer registry mechanism to manage memory and provide search functionalities. (non-predicate version)
1365///
1366/// @detail NOTE: This is thread-unsafe implementation (although it contains lock function, it does not use these functions)
1367/// of AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>. Any implementation of this class should be
1368/// explicitly (by using lock functions)
1369template <typename T_Ptr, typename T_Key = const char*>
1370class Registry : public AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::unordered_map<T_Key, T_Ptr*>> {
1371 public:
1372 typedef typename Registry<T_Ptr, T_Key>::iterator iterator;
1373 typedef typename Registry<T_Ptr, T_Key>::const_iterator const_iterator;
1374
1375 Registry(void) {}
1376
1377 /// @brief Copy constructor that is useful for base classes. Try to avoid this constructor, use move constructor.
1378 Registry(const Registry& sr) : AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::vector<T_Ptr*>>() {
1379 if (this == &sr) {
1380 return;
1381 }
1382 this->reinitDeepCopy(sr);
1383 }
1384
1385 /// @brief Assignment operator that unregisters all the existing registries and deeply copies each of repo element
1386 /// @see unregisterAll()
1387 /// @see deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry&)
1388 Registry& operator=(const Registry& sr) {
1389 if (this == &sr) {
1390 return *this;
1391 }
1392 this->reinitDeepCopy(sr);
1393 return *this;
1394 }
1395
1396 virtual ~Registry(void) {
1397 unregisterAll();
1398 }
1399
1400 protected:
1401 virtual void unregisterAll(void) ELPP_FINAL {
1402 if (!this->empty()) {
1403 for (auto&& curr : this->list()) {
1404 base::utils::safeDelete(curr.second);
1405 }
1406 this->list().clear();
1407 }
1408 }
1409
1410/// @brief Registers new registry to repository.
1411 virtual void registerNew(const T_Key& uniqKey, T_Ptr* ptr) ELPP_FINAL {
1412 unregister(uniqKey);
1413 this->list().insert(std::make_pair(uniqKey, ptr));
1414 }
1415
1416/// @brief Unregisters single entry mapped to specified unique key
1417 void unregister(const T_Key& uniqKey) {
1418 T_Ptr* existing = get(uniqKey);
1419 if (existing != nullptr) {
1420 this->list().erase(uniqKey);
1421 base::utils::safeDelete(existing);
1422 }
1423 }
1424
1425/// @brief Gets pointer from repository. If none found, nullptr is returned.
1426 T_Ptr* get(const T_Key& uniqKey) {
1427 iterator it = this->list().find(uniqKey);
1428 return it == this->list().end()
1429 ? nullptr
1430 : it->second;
1431 }
1432
1433 private:
1434 virtual void deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::unordered_map<T_Key, T_Ptr*>>& sr) ELPP_FINAL {
1435 for (const_iterator it = sr.cbegin(); it != sr.cend(); ++it) {
1436 registerNew(it->first, new T_Ptr(*it->second));
1437 }
1438 }
1439};
1440
1441/// @brief A pointer registry mechanism to manage memory and provide search functionalities. (predicate version)
1442///
1443/// @detail NOTE: This is thread-unsafe implementation of AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, Container>. Any implementation of this class
1444/// should be made thread-safe explicitly
1445template <typename T_Ptr, typename Pred>
1446class RegistryWithPred : public AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::vector<T_Ptr*>> {
1447 public:
1448 typedef typename RegistryWithPred<T_Ptr, Pred>::iterator iterator;
1449 typedef typename RegistryWithPred<T_Ptr, Pred>::const_iterator const_iterator;
1450
1451 RegistryWithPred(void) {
1452 }
1453
1454 virtual ~RegistryWithPred(void) {
1455 unregisterAll();
1456 }
1457
1458 /// @brief Copy constructor that is useful for base classes. Try to avoid this constructor, use move constructor.
1459 RegistryWithPred(const RegistryWithPred& sr) : AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::vector<T_Ptr*>>() {
1460 if (this == &sr) {
1461 return;
1462 }
1463 this->reinitDeepCopy(sr);
1464 }
1465
1466 /// @brief Assignment operator that unregisters all the existing registries and deeply copies each of repo element
1467 /// @see unregisterAll()
1468 /// @see deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry&)
1469 RegistryWithPred& operator=(const RegistryWithPred& sr) {
1470 if (this == &sr) {
1471 return *this;
1472 }
1473 this->reinitDeepCopy(sr);
1474 return *this;
1475 }
1476
1477 friend base::type::ostream_t& operator<<(base::type::ostream_t& os, const RegistryWithPred& sr) {
1478 for (const_iterator it = sr.list().begin(); it != sr.list().end(); ++it) {
1479 os << ELPP_LITERAL(" ") << **it << ELPP_LITERAL("\n");
1480 }
1481 return os;
1482 }
1483
1484 protected:
1485 virtual void unregisterAll(void) ELPP_FINAL {
1486 if (!this->empty()) {
1487 for (auto&& curr : this->list()) {
1488 base::utils::safeDelete(curr);
1489 }
1490 this->list().clear();
1491 }
1492 }
1493
1494 virtual void unregister(T_Ptr*& ptr) ELPP_FINAL {
1495 if (ptr) {
1496 iterator iter = this->begin();
1497 for (; iter != this->end(); ++iter) {
1498 if (ptr == *iter) {
1499 break;
1500 }
1501 }
1502 if (iter != this->end() && *iter != nullptr) {
1503 this->list().erase(iter);
1504 base::utils::safeDelete(*iter);
1505 }
1506 }
1507 }
1508
1509 virtual inline void registerNew(T_Ptr* ptr) ELPP_FINAL {
1510 this->list().push_back(ptr);
1511 }
1512
1513/// @brief Gets pointer from repository with specified arguments. Arguments are passed to predicate
1514/// in order to validate pointer.
1515 template <typename T, typename T2>
1516 T_Ptr* get(const T& arg1, const T2 arg2) {
1517 iterator iter = std::find_if(this->list().begin(), this->list().end(), Pred(arg1, arg2));
1518 if (iter != this->list().end() && *iter != nullptr) {
1519 return *iter;
1520 }
1521 return nullptr;
1522 }
1523
1524 private:
1525 virtual void deepCopy(const AbstractRegistry<T_Ptr, std::vector<T_Ptr*>>& sr) {
1526 for (const_iterator it = sr.list().begin(); it != sr.list().end(); ++it) {
1527 registerNew(new T_Ptr(**it));
1528 }
1529 }
1530};
1531class Utils {
1532 public:
1533 template <typename T, typename TPtr>
1534 static bool installCallback(const std::string& id, std::unordered_map<std::string, TPtr>* mapT) {
1535 if (mapT->find(id) == mapT->end()) {
1536 mapT->insert(std::make_pair(id, TPtr(new T())));
1537 return true;
1538 }
1539 return false;
1540 }
1541
1542 template <typename T, typename TPtr>
1543 static void uninstallCallback(const std::string& id, std::unordered_map<std::string, TPtr>* mapT) {
1544 if (mapT->find(id) != mapT->end()) {
1545 mapT->erase(id);
1546 }
1547 }
1548
1549 template <typename T, typename TPtr>
1550 static T* callback(const std::string& id, std::unordered_map<std::string, TPtr>* mapT) {
1551 typename std::unordered_map<std::string, TPtr>::iterator iter = mapT->find(id);
1552 if (iter != mapT->end()) {
1553 return static_cast<T*>(iter->second.get());
1554 }
1555 return nullptr;
1556 }
1557};
1558} // namespace utils
1559} // namespace base

1569 loggable.log(os);
1570 return os;
1571 }
1572};

1641/// @brief Resolving function for format specifier
1642typedef std::function<std::string(const LogMessage*)> FormatSpecifierValueResolver;
1643/// @brief User-provided custom format specifier

1645/// @see FormatSpecifierValueResolver
1646class CustomFormatSpecifier {

1664/// @brief Represents single configuration that has representing level, configuration type and a string based value.
1665///
1666/// @detail String based value means any value either its boolean, integer or string itself, it will be embedded inside quotes
1667/// and will be parsed later.
1668///
1669/// Consider some examples below:
1670/// * el::Configuration confEnabledInfo(el::Level::Info, el::ConfigurationType::Enabled, "true");
1671/// * el::Configuration confMaxLogFileSizeInfo(el::Level::Info, el::ConfigurationType::MaxLogFileSize, "2048");
1672/// * el::Configuration confFilenameInfo(el::Level::Info, el::ConfigurationType::Filename, "/var/log/my.log");
1673class Configuration : public Loggable {
1674 public:
1675 Configuration(const Configuration& c);
1676 Configuration& operator=(const Configuration& c);
1677
1678 virtual ~Configuration(void) {
1679 }
1680
1681 /// @brief Full constructor used to sets value of configuration
1682 Configuration(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value);
1683
1684 /// @brief Gets level of current configuration
1685 inline Level level(void) const {
1686 return m_level;
1687 }
1688
1689 /// @brief Gets configuration type of current configuration
1690 inline ConfigurationType configurationType(void) const {
1691 return m_configurationType;
1692 }
1693
1694 /// @brief Gets string based configuration value
1695 inline const std::string& value(void) const {
1696 return m_value;
1697 }
1698
1699 /// @brief Set string based configuration value
1700 /// @param value Value to set. Values have to be std::string; For boolean values use "true", "false", for any integral values
1701 /// use them in quotes. They will be parsed when configuring
1702 inline void setValue(const std::string& value) {
1703 m_value = value;
1704 }
1705
1706 virtual void log(el::base::type::ostream_t& os) const;
1707
1708 /// @brief Used to find configuration from configuration (pointers) repository. Avoid using it.
1709 class Predicate {
1710 public:
1711 Predicate(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType);
1712
1713 bool operator()(const Configuration* conf) const;
1714
1715 private:
1716 Level m_level;
1717 ConfigurationType m_configurationType;
1718 };
1719
1720 private:
1721 Level m_level;
1722 ConfigurationType m_configurationType;
1723 std::string m_value;
1724};

1726/// @brief Thread-safe Configuration repository
1727///
1728/// @detail This repository represents configurations for all the levels and configuration type mapped to a value.
1729class Configurations : public base::utils::RegistryWithPred<Configuration, Configuration::Predicate> {
1730 public:
1731 /// @brief Default constructor with empty repository
1732 Configurations(void);
1733
1734 /// @brief Constructor used to set configurations using configuration file.
1735 /// @param configurationFile Full path to configuration file
1736 /// @param useDefaultsForRemaining Lets you set the remaining configurations to default.
1737 /// @param base If provided, this configuration will be based off existing repository that this argument is pointing to.
1738 /// @see parseFromFile(const std::string&, Configurations* base)
1739 /// @see setRemainingToDefault()
1740 Configurations(const std::string& configurationFile, bool useDefaultsForRemaining = true,
1741 Configurations* base = nullptr);
1742
1743 virtual ~Configurations(void) {
1744 }
1745
1746 /// @brief Parses configuration from file.
1747 /// @param configurationFile Full path to configuration file
1748 /// @param base Configurations to base new configuration repository off. This value is used when you want to use
1749 /// existing Configurations to base all the values and then set rest of configuration via configuration file.
1750 /// @return True if successfully parsed, false otherwise. You may define 'ELPP_DEBUG_ASSERT_FAILURE' to make sure you
1751 /// do not proceed without successful parse.
1752 bool parseFromFile(const std::string& configurationFile, Configurations* base = nullptr);
1753
1754 /// @brief Parse configurations from configuration string.
1755 ///
1756 /// @detail This configuration string has same syntax as configuration file contents. Make sure all the necessary
1757 /// new line characters are provided.
1758 /// @param base Configurations to base new configuration repository off. This value is used when you want to use
1759 /// existing Configurations to base all the values and then set rest of configuration via configuration text.
1760 /// @return True if successfully parsed, false otherwise. You may define 'ELPP_DEBUG_ASSERT_FAILURE' to make sure you
1761 /// do not proceed without successful parse.
1762 bool parseFromText(const std::string& configurationsString, Configurations* base = nullptr);
1763
1764 /// @brief Sets configuration based-off an existing configurations.
1765 /// @param base Pointer to existing configurations.
1766 void setFromBase(Configurations* base);
1767
1768 /// @brief Determines whether or not specified configuration type exists in the repository.
1769 ///
1770 /// @detail Returns as soon as first level is found.
1771 /// @param configurationType Type of configuration to check existence for.
1772 bool hasConfiguration(ConfigurationType configurationType);
1773
1774 /// @brief Determines whether or not specified configuration type exists for specified level
1775 /// @param level Level to check
1776 /// @param configurationType Type of configuration to check existence for.
1777 bool hasConfiguration(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType);
1778
1779 /// @brief Sets value of configuration for specified level.
1780 ///
1781 /// @detail Any existing configuration for specified level will be replaced. Also note that configuration types
1782 /// ConfigurationType::SubsecondPrecision and ConfigurationType::PerformanceTracking will be ignored if not set for
1783 /// Level::Global because these configurations are not dependant on level.
1784 /// @param level Level to set configuration for (el::Level).
1785 /// @param configurationType Type of configuration (el::ConfigurationType)
1786 /// @param value A string based value. Regardless of what the data type of configuration is, it will always be string
1787 /// from users' point of view. This is then parsed later to be used internally.
1788 /// @see Configuration::setValue(const std::string& value)
1789 /// @see el::Level
1790 /// @see el::ConfigurationType
1791 void set(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value);
1792
1793 /// @brief Sets single configuration based on other single configuration.
1794 /// @see set(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value)
1795 void set(Configuration* conf);
1796
1797 inline Configuration* get(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType) {
1798 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
1799 return RegistryWithPred<Configuration, Configuration::Predicate>::get(level, configurationType);
1800 }
1801
1802 /// @brief Sets configuration for all levels.
1803 /// @param configurationType Type of configuration
1804 /// @param value String based value
1805 /// @see Configurations::set(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value)
1806 inline void setGlobally(ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value) {
1807 setGlobally(configurationType, value, false);
1808 }
1809
1810 /// @brief Clears repository so that all the configurations are unset
1811 inline void clear(void) {
1812 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
1813 unregisterAll();
1814 }
1815
1816 /// @brief Gets configuration file used in parsing this configurations.
1817 ///
1818 /// @detail If this repository was set manually or by text this returns empty string.
1819 inline const std::string& configurationFile(void) const {
1820 return m_configurationFile;
1821 }
1822
1823 /// @brief Sets configurations to "factory based" configurations.
1824 void setToDefault(void);
1825
1826 /// @brief Lets you set the remaining configurations to default.
1827 ///
1828 /// @detail By remaining, it means that the level/type a configuration does not exist for.
1829 /// This function is useful when you want to minimize chances of failures, e.g, if you have a configuration file that sets
1830 /// configuration for all the configurations except for Enabled or not, we use this so that ENABLED is set to default i.e,
1831 /// true. If you dont do this explicitly (either by calling this function or by using second param in Constructor
1832 /// and try to access a value, an error is thrown
1833 void setRemainingToDefault(void);
1834
1835 /// @brief Parser used internally to parse configurations from file or text.
1836 ///
1837 /// @detail This class makes use of base::utils::Str.
1838 /// You should not need this unless you are working on some tool for Easylogging++
1839 class Parser : base::StaticClass {
1840 public:
1841 /// @brief Parses configuration from file.
1842 /// @param configurationFile Full path to configuration file
1843 /// @param sender Sender configurations pointer. Usually 'this' is used from calling class
1844 /// @param base Configurations to base new configuration repository off. This value is used when you want to use
1845 /// existing Configurations to base all the values and then set rest of configuration via configuration file.
1846 /// @return True if successfully parsed, false otherwise. You may define '_STOP_ON_FIRSTELPP_ASSERTION' to make sure you
1847 /// do not proceed without successful parse.
1848 static bool parseFromFile(const std::string& configurationFile, Configurations* sender,
1849 Configurations* base = nullptr);
1850
1851 /// @brief Parse configurations from configuration string.
1852 ///
1853 /// @detail This configuration string has same syntax as configuration file contents. Make sure all the necessary
1854 /// new line characters are provided. You may define '_STOP_ON_FIRSTELPP_ASSERTION' to make sure you
1855 /// do not proceed without successful parse (This is recommended)
1856 /// @param configurationsString the configuration in plain text format
1857 /// @param sender Sender configurations pointer. Usually 'this' is used from calling class
1858 /// @param base Configurations to base new configuration repository off. This value is used when you want to use
1859 /// existing Configurations to base all the values and then set rest of configuration via configuration text.
1860 /// @return True if successfully parsed, false otherwise.
1861 static bool parseFromText(const std::string& configurationsString, Configurations* sender,
1862 Configurations* base = nullptr);
1863
1864 private:
1865 friend class el::Loggers;
1866 static void ignoreComments(std::string* line);
1867 static bool isLevel(const std::string& line);
1868 static bool isComment(const std::string& line);
1869 static inline bool isConfig(const std::string& line);
1870 static bool parseLine(std::string* line, std::string* currConfigStr, std::string* currLevelStr, Level* currLevel,
1871 Configurations* conf);
1872 };
1873
1874 private:
1875 std::string m_configurationFile;
1876 bool m_isFromFile;
1877 friend class el::Loggers;
1878
1879 /// @brief Unsafely sets configuration if does not already exist
1880 void unsafeSetIfNotExist(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value);
1881
1882 /// @brief Thread unsafe set
1883 void unsafeSet(Level level, ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value);
1884
1885 /// @brief Sets configurations for all levels including Level::Global if includeGlobalLevel is true
1886 /// @see Configurations::setGlobally(ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value)
1887 void setGlobally(ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value, bool includeGlobalLevel);
1888
1889 /// @brief Sets configurations (Unsafely) for all levels including Level::Global if includeGlobalLevel is true
1890 /// @see Configurations::setGlobally(ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value)
1891 void unsafeSetGlobally(ConfigurationType configurationType, const std::string& value, bool includeGlobalLevel);
1892};

1952 template <typename Conf_T>
1953 inline Conf_T getConfigByVal(Level level, const std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>* confMap, const char* confName) {
1954 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
1955 return unsafeGetConfigByVal(level, confMap, confName); // This is not unsafe anymore - mutex locked in scope
1956 }
1957
1958 template <typename Conf_T>
1959 inline Conf_T& getConfigByRef(Level level, std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>* confMap, const char* confName) {
1960 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
1961 return unsafeGetConfigByRef(level, confMap, confName); // This is not unsafe anymore - mutex locked in scope
1962 }
1963
1964 template <typename Conf_T>
1965 Conf_T unsafeGetConfigByVal(Level level, const std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>* confMap, const char* confName) {
1966 ELPP_UNUSED(confName);
1967 typename std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>::const_iterator it = confMap->find(level);
1968 if (it == confMap->end()) {
1969 try {
1970 return confMap->at(Level::Global);
1971 } catch (...) {
1972 ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR("Unable to get configuration [" << confName << "] for level ["
1973 << LevelHelper::convertToString(level) << "]"
1974 << std::endl << "Please ensure you have properly configured logger.", false);
1975 return Conf_T();
1976 }
1977 }
1978 return it->second;
1979 }
1980
1981 template <typename Conf_T>
1982 Conf_T& unsafeGetConfigByRef(Level level, std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>* confMap, const char* confName) {
1983 ELPP_UNUSED(confName);
1984 typename std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>::iterator it = confMap->find(level);
1985 if (it == confMap->end()) {
1986 try {
1987 return confMap->at(Level::Global);
1988 } catch (...) {
1989 ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR("Unable to get configuration [" << confName << "] for level ["
1990 << LevelHelper::convertToString(level) << "]"
1991 << std::endl << "Please ensure you have properly configured logger.", false);
1992 }
1993 }
1994 return it->second;
1995 }
1996
1997 template <typename Conf_T>
1998 void setValue(Level level, const Conf_T& value, std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>* confMap,
1999 bool includeGlobalLevel = true) {
2000 // If map is empty and we are allowed to add into generic level (Level::Global), do it!
2001 if (confMap->empty() && includeGlobalLevel) {
2002 confMap->insert(std::make_pair(Level::Global, value));
2003 return;
2004 }
2005 // If same value exist in generic level already, dont add it to explicit level
2006 typename std::unordered_map<Level, Conf_T>::iterator it = confMap->find(Level::Global);
2007 if (it != confMap->end() && it->second == value) {
2008 return;
2009 }
2010 // Now make sure we dont double up values if we really need to add it to explicit level
2011 it = confMap->find(level);
2012 if (it == confMap->end()) {
2013 // Value not found for level, add new
2014 confMap->insert(std::make_pair(level, value));
2015 } else {
2016 // Value found, just update value
2017 confMap->at(level) = value;
2018 }
2019 }

2021 void build(Configurations* configurations);
2022 unsigned long getULong(std::string confVal);
2023 std::string resolveFilename(const std::string& filename);
2024 void insertFile(Level level, const std::string& fullFilename);
2025 bool unsafeValidateFileRolling(Level level, const PreRollOutCallback& preRollOutCallback);
2026
2027 inline bool validateFileRolling(Level level, const PreRollOutCallback& preRollOutCallback) {
2028 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2029 return unsafeValidateFileRolling(level, preRollOutCallback);
2030 }

2032/// @brief Class that keeps record of current line hit for occasional logging
2033class HitCounter {
2034 public:
2035 HitCounter(void) :
2036 m_filename(""),
2037 m_lineNumber(0),
2038 m_hitCounts(0) {
2039 }
2040
2041 HitCounter(const char* filename, base::type::LineNumber lineNumber) :
2042 m_filename(filename),
2043 m_lineNumber(lineNumber),
2044 m_hitCounts(0) {
2045 }
2046
2047 HitCounter(const HitCounter& hitCounter) :
2048 m_filename(hitCounter.m_filename),
2049 m_lineNumber(hitCounter.m_lineNumber),
2050 m_hitCounts(hitCounter.m_hitCounts) {
2051 }
2052
2053 HitCounter& operator=(const HitCounter& hitCounter) {
2054 if (&hitCounter != this) {
2055 m_filename = hitCounter.m_filename;
2056 m_lineNumber = hitCounter.m_lineNumber;
2057 m_hitCounts = hitCounter.m_hitCounts;
2058 }
2059 return *this;
2060 }
2061
2062 virtual ~HitCounter(void) {
2063 }
2064
2065 /// @brief Resets location of current hit counter
2066 inline void resetLocation(const char* filename, base::type::LineNumber lineNumber) {
2067 m_filename = filename;
2068 m_lineNumber = lineNumber;
2069 }
2070
2071 /// @brief Validates hit counts and resets it if necessary
2072 inline void validateHitCounts(std::size_t n) {
2073 if (m_hitCounts >= base::consts::kMaxLogPerCounter) {
2074 m_hitCounts = (n >= 1 ? base::consts::kMaxLogPerCounter % n : 0);
2075 }
2076 ++m_hitCounts;
2077 }
2078
2079 inline const char* filename(void) const {
2080 return m_filename;
2081 }
2082
2083 inline base::type::LineNumber lineNumber(void) const {
2084 return m_lineNumber;
2085 }
2086
2087 inline std::size_t hitCounts(void) const {
2088 return m_hitCounts;
2089 }
2090
2091 inline void increment(void) {
2092 ++m_hitCounts;
2093 }
2094
2095 class Predicate {
2096 public:
2097 Predicate(const char* filename, base::type::LineNumber lineNumber)
2098 : m_filename(filename),
2099 m_lineNumber(lineNumber) {
2100 }
2101 inline bool operator()(const HitCounter* counter) {
2102 return ((counter != nullptr) &&
2103 (strcmp(counter->m_filename, m_filename) == 0) &&
2104 (counter->m_lineNumber == m_lineNumber));
2105 }
2106
2107 private:
2108 const char* m_filename;
2109 base::type::LineNumber m_lineNumber;
2110 };
2111
2112 private:
2113 const char* m_filename;
2114 base::type::LineNumber m_lineNumber;
2115 std::size_t m_hitCounts;
2116};

2454class LogMessage {

2512class AsyncLogQueue : public base::threading::ThreadSafe {
2513 public:
2514 virtual ~AsyncLogQueue() {
2515 ELPP_INTERNAL_INFO(6, "~AsyncLogQueue");
2516 }
2517
2518 inline AsyncLogItem next(void) {
2519 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2520 AsyncLogItem result = m_queue.front();
2521 m_queue.pop();
2522 return result;
2523 }
2524
2525 inline void push(const AsyncLogItem& item) {
2526 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2527 m_queue.push(item);
2528 }
2529 inline void pop(void) {
2530 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2531 m_queue.pop();
2532 }
2533 inline AsyncLogItem front(void) {
2534 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2535 return m_queue.front();
2536 }
2537 inline bool empty(void) {
2538 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(lock());
2539 return m_queue.empty();
2540 }
2541 private:
2542 std::queue<AsyncLogItem> m_queue;
2543};

2676 /// @brief Sets thread name for current thread. Requires std::thread
2677 inline void setThreadName(const std::string& name) {
2678 if (name.empty()) return;
2679 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(m_threadNamesLock);
2680 m_threadNames[base::threading::getCurrentThreadId()] = name;
2681 }
2682
2683 inline std::string getThreadName(const std::string& threadId) {
2684 base::threading::ScopedLock scopedLock(m_threadNamesLock);
2685 std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string>::const_iterator it = m_threadNames.find(threadId);
2686 if (it == m_threadNames.end()) {
2687 return threadId;
2688 }
2689 return it->second;
2690 }

2704 std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string> m_threadNames;

2785#if defined(ELPP_STL_LOGGING)
2786/// @brief Workarounds to write some STL logs
2787///
2788/// @detail There is workaround needed to loop through some stl containers. In order to do that, we need iterable containers
2789/// of same type and provide iterator interface and pass it on to writeIterator().
2790/// Remember, this is passed by value in constructor so that we dont change original containers.
2791/// This operation is as expensive as Big-O(std::min(class_.size(), base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer))
2792namespace workarounds {
2793/// @brief Abstract IterableContainer template that provides interface for iterable classes of type T
2794template <typename T, typename Container>
2795class IterableContainer {
2796 public:
2797 typedef typename Container::iterator iterator;
2798 typedef typename Container::const_iterator const_iterator;
2799 IterableContainer(void) {}
2800 virtual ~IterableContainer(void) {}
2801 iterator begin(void) {
2802 return getContainer().begin();
2803 }
2804 iterator end(void) {
2805 return getContainer().end();
2806 }
2807 private:
2808 virtual Container& getContainer(void) = 0;
2809};
2810/// @brief Implements IterableContainer and provides iterable std::priority_queue class
2811template<typename T, typename Container = std::vector<T>, typename Comparator = std::less<typename Container::value_type>>
2812class IterablePriorityQueue : public IterableContainer<T, Container>,
2813 public std::priority_queue<T, Container, Comparator> {
2814 public:
2815 IterablePriorityQueue(std::priority_queue<T, Container, Comparator> queue_) {
2816 std::size_t count_ = 0;
2817 while (++count_ < base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer && !queue_.empty()) {
2818 this->push(queue_.top());
2819 queue_.pop();
2820 }
2821 }
2822 private:
2823 inline Container& getContainer(void) {
2824 return this->c;
2825 }
2826};
2827/// @brief Implements IterableContainer and provides iterable std::queue class
2828template<typename T, typename Container = std::deque<T>>
2829class IterableQueue : public IterableContainer<T, Container>, public std::queue<T, Container> {
2830 public:
2831 IterableQueue(std::queue<T, Container> queue_) {
2832 std::size_t count_ = 0;
2833 while (++count_ < base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer && !queue_.empty()) {
2834 this->push(queue_.front());
2835 queue_.pop();
2836 }
2837 }
2838 private:
2839 inline Container& getContainer(void) {
2840 return this->c;
2841 }
2842};
2843/// @brief Implements IterableContainer and provides iterable std::stack class
2844template<typename T, typename Container = std::deque<T>>
2845class IterableStack : public IterableContainer<T, Container>, public std::stack<T, Container> {
2846 public:
2847 IterableStack(std::stack<T, Container> stack_) {
2848 std::size_t count_ = 0;
2849 while (++count_ < base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer && !stack_.empty()) {
2850 this->push(stack_.top());
2851 stack_.pop();
2852 }
2853 }
2854 private:
2855 inline Container& getContainer(void) {
2856 return this->c;
2857 }
2858};
2859} // namespace workarounds
2860#endif // defined(ELPP_STL_LOGGING)

3024 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QList)
3025 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QVector)
3026 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QQueue)
3027 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QSet)
3028 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QLinkedList)
3029 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(QStack)
3030 template <typename First, typename Second>
3031 MessageBuilder& operator<<(const QPair<First, Second>& pair_) {
3032 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("(");
3033 operator << (static_cast<First>(pair_.first));
3034 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(", ");
3035 operator << (static_cast<Second>(pair_.second));
3036 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(")");
3037 return *this;
3038 }
3039 template <typename K, typename V>
3040 MessageBuilder& operator<<(const QMap<K, V>& map_) {
3041 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("[");
3042 QList<K> keys = map_.keys();
3043 typename QList<K>::const_iterator begin = keys.begin();
3044 typename QList<K>::const_iterator end = keys.end();
3045 int max_ = static_cast<int>(base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer); // to prevent warning
3046 for (int index_ = 0; begin != end && index_ < max_; ++index_, ++begin) {
3047 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("(");
3048 operator << (static_cast<K>(*begin));
3049 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(", ");
3050 operator << (static_cast<V>(map_.value(*begin)));
3051 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(")");
3052 m_logger->stream() << ((index_ < keys.size() -1) ? m_containerLogSeparator : ELPP_LITERAL(""));
3053 }
3054 if (begin != end) {
3055 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("...");
3056 }
3057 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3058 return *this;
3059 }
3060 template <typename K, typename V>
3061 inline MessageBuilder& operator<<(const QMultiMap<K, V>& map_) {
3062 operator << (static_cast<QMap<K, V>>(map_));
3063 return *this;
3064 }
3065 template <typename K, typename V>
3066 MessageBuilder& operator<<(const QHash<K, V>& hash_) {
3067 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("[");
3068 QList<K> keys = hash_.keys();
3069 typename QList<K>::const_iterator begin = keys.begin();
3070 typename QList<K>::const_iterator end = keys.end();
3071 int max_ = static_cast<int>(base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer); // prevent type warning
3072 for (int index_ = 0; begin != end && index_ < max_; ++index_, ++begin) {
3073 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("(");
3074 operator << (static_cast<K>(*begin));
3075 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(", ");
3076 operator << (static_cast<V>(hash_.value(*begin)));
3077 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL(")");
3078 m_logger->stream() << ((index_ < keys.size() -1) ? m_containerLogSeparator : ELPP_LITERAL(""));
3079 }
3080 if (begin != end) {
3081 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("...");
3082 }
3083 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3084 return *this;
3085 }
3086 template <typename K, typename V>
3087 inline MessageBuilder& operator<<(const QMultiHash<K, V>& multiHash_) {
3088 operator << (static_cast<QHash<K, V>>(multiHash_));
3089 return *this;
3090 }
3091#endif // defined(ELPP_QT_LOGGING)
3092#if defined(ELPP_BOOST_LOGGING)
3093 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_TWO_ARG(boost::container::vector)
3094 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_TWO_ARG(boost::container::stable_vector)
3095 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_TWO_ARG(boost::container::list)
3096 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_TWO_ARG(boost::container::deque)
3097 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_FOUR_ARG(boost::container::map)
3098 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_FOUR_ARG(boost::container::flat_map)
3099 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_THREE_ARG(boost::container::set)
3100 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_THREE_ARG(boost::container::flat_set)
3101#endif // defined(ELPP_BOOST_LOGGING)

3103 /// @brief Macro used internally that can be used externally to make containers easylogging++ friendly
3104 ///
3105 /// @detail This macro expands to write an ostream& operator<< for container. This container is expected to
3106 /// have begin() and end() methods that return respective iterators
3107 /// @param ContainerType Type of container e.g, MyList from WX_DECLARE_LIST(int, MyList); in wxwidgets
3108 /// @param SizeMethod Method used to get size of container.
3109 /// @param ElementInstance Instance of element to be fed out. Instance name is "elem". See WXELPP_ENABLED macro
3110 /// for an example usage
3111#define MAKE_CONTAINERELPP_FRIENDLY(ContainerType, SizeMethod, ElementInstance) el
3112 ::base::type::ostream_t& operator<<(el::base::type::ostream_t& ss, const ContainerType& container) {const
3113 el::base::type::char_t* sep = ELPP->hasFlag(el::LoggingFlag::NewLineForContainer) ? ELPP_LITERAL
3114 ("\n ") : ELPP_LITERAL(", ");ContainerType
3115 ::const_iterator elem = container.begin();ContainerType
3116 ::const_iterator endElem = container.end();std
3117 ::size_t size_ = container.SizeMethod; ss
3118 << ELPP_LITERAL("[");for
3119 (std::size_t i = 0; elem != endElem && i < el::base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer; ++i, ++elem) { ss
3120 << ElementInstance;ss
3121 << ((i < size_ - 1) ? sep : ELPP_LITERAL(""));\
3122}if
3123 (elem != endElem) {ss
3124 << ELPP_LITERAL("...");\
3125}ss
3126 << ELPP_LITERAL("]");return
3127 ss;\
3128}
3129#if defined(ELPP_WXWIDGETS_LOGGING)
3130 ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG(wxVector)
3131# define ELPP_WX_PTR_ENABLED(ContainerType) MAKE_CONTAINERELPP_FRIENDLY(ContainerType, size(), *(*elem))
3132# define ELPP_WX_ENABLED(ContainerType) MAKE_CONTAINERELPP_FRIENDLY(ContainerType, size(), (*elem))
3133# define ELPP_WX_HASH_MAP_ENABLED(ContainerType) MAKE_CONTAINERELPP_FRIENDLY(ContainerType, size(), ELPP_LITERAL
3134 ("(") << elem->first << ELPP_LITERAL(", ") << elem->second << ELPP_LITERAL(")")
3135#else
3136# define ELPP_WX_PTR_ENABLED(ContainerType)
3137# define ELPP_WX_ENABLED(ContainerType)
3138# define ELPP_WX_HASH_MAP_ENABLED(ContainerType)
3139#endif // defined(ELPP_WXWIDGETS_LOGGING)
3140 // Other classes
3141 template <class Class>
3142 ELPP_SIMPLE_LOG(const Class&)
3143#undef ELPP_SIMPLE_LOG
3144#undef ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_ONE_ARG
3145#undef ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_TWO_ARG
3146#undef ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_THREE_ARG
3147#undef ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_FOUR_ARG
3148#undef ELPP_ITERATOR_CONTAINER_LOG_FIVE_ARG
3149 private:
3150 Logger* m_logger;
3151 const base::type::char_t* m_containerLogSeparator;
3152
3153 template<class Iterator>
3154 MessageBuilder& writeIterator(Iterator begin_, Iterator end_, std::size_t size_) {
3155 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("[");
3156 for (std::size_t i = 0; begin_ != end_ && i < base::consts::kMaxLogPerContainer; ++i, ++begin_) {
3157 operator << (*begin_);
3158 m_logger->stream() << ((i < size_ - 1) ? m_containerLogSeparator : ELPP_LITERAL(""));
3159 }
3160 if (begin_ != end_) {
3161 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("...");
3162 }
3163 m_logger->stream() << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3164 if (ELPP->hasFlag(LoggingFlag::AutoSpacing)) {
3165 m_logger->stream() << " ";
3166 }
3167 return *this;
3168 }
3169};

3262// Logging from Logger class. Why this is here? Because we have Storage and Writer class available
3263#if ELPP_VARIADIC_TEMPLATES_SUPPORTED
3264template <typename T, typename... Args>
3265void Logger::log_(Level level, int vlevel, const char* s, const T& value, const Args&... args) {
3266 base::MessageBuilder b;
3267 b.initialize(this);
3268 while (*s) {
3269 if (*s == base::consts::kFormatSpecifierChar) {
3270 if (*(s + 1) == base::consts::kFormatSpecifierChar) {
3271 ++s;
3272 } else {
3273 if (*(s + 1) == base::consts::kFormatSpecifierCharValue) {
3274 ++s;
3275 b << value;
3276 log_(level, vlevel, ++s, args...);
3277 return;
3278 }
3279 }
3280 }
3281 b << *s++;
3282 }
3283 ELPP_INTERNAL_ERROR("Too many arguments provided. Unable to handle. Please provide more format specifiers", false);
3284}
3285template <typename T>
3286void Logger::log_(Level level, int vlevel, const T& log) {
3287 if (level == Level::Verbose) {
3288 if (ELPP->vRegistry()->allowed(vlevel, __FILE__)) {
3289 base::Writer(Level::Verbose, "FILE", 0, "FUNCTION",
3290 base::DispatchAction::NormalLog, vlevel).construct(this, false) << log;
3291 } else {
3292 stream().str(ELPP_LITERAL(""));
3293 releaseLock();
3294 }
3295 } else {
3296 base::Writer(level, "FILE", 0, "FUNCTION").construct(this, false) << log;
3297 }
3298}
3299template <typename T, typename... Args>
3300inline void Logger::log(Level level, const char* s, const T& value, const Args&... args) {
3301 acquireLock(); // released in Writer!
3302 log_(level, 0, s, value, args...);
3303}
3304template <typename T>
3305inline void Logger::log(Level level, const T& log) {
3306 acquireLock(); // released in Writer!
3307 log_(level, 0, log);
3308}
3309# if ELPP_VERBOSE_LOG
3310template <typename T, typename... Args>
3311inline void Logger::verbose(int vlevel, const char* s, const T& value, const Args&... args) {
3312 acquireLock(); // released in Writer!
3313 log_(el::Level::Verbose, vlevel, s, value, args...);
3314}
3315template <typename T>
3316inline void Logger::verbose(int vlevel, const T& log) {
3317 acquireLock(); // released in Writer!
3318 log_(el::Level::Verbose, vlevel, log);
3319}
3320# else
3321template <typename T, typename... Args>
3322inline void Logger::verbose(int, const char*, const T&, const Args&...) {
3323 return;
3324}

3463/// @brief Represents performanceTracker block of code that conditionally adds performance status to log
3464/// either when goes outside the scope of when checkpoint() is called
3465class PerformanceTracker : public base::threading::ThreadSafe, public Loggable {
3466 public:
3467 PerformanceTracker(const std::string& blockName,
3468 base::TimestampUnit timestampUnit = base::TimestampUnit::Millisecond,
3469 const std::string& loggerId = std::string(el::base::consts::kPerformanceLoggerId),
3470 bool scopedLog = true, Level level = base::consts::kPerformanceTrackerDefaultLevel);
3471 /// @brief Copy constructor
3472 PerformanceTracker(const PerformanceTracker& t) :
3473 m_blockName(t.m_blockName), m_timestampUnit(t.m_timestampUnit), m_loggerId(t.m_loggerId), m_scopedLog(t.m_scopedLog),
3474 m_level(t.m_level), m_hasChecked(t.m_hasChecked), m_lastCheckpointId(t.m_lastCheckpointId), m_enabled(t.m_enabled),
3475 m_startTime(t.m_startTime), m_endTime(t.m_endTime), m_lastCheckpointTime(t.m_lastCheckpointTime) {
3476 }
3477 virtual ~PerformanceTracker(void);
3478 /// @brief A checkpoint for current performanceTracker block.
3479 void checkpoint(const std::string& id = std::string(), const char* file = __FILE__,
3480 base::type::LineNumber line = __LINE__,
3481 const char* func = "");
3482 inline Level level(void) const {
3483 return m_level;
3484 }
3485 private:
3486 std::string m_blockName;
3487 base::TimestampUnit m_timestampUnit;
3488 std::string m_loggerId;
3489 bool m_scopedLog;
3490 Level m_level;
3491 bool m_hasChecked;
3492 std::string m_lastCheckpointId;
3493 bool m_enabled;
3494 struct timeval m_startTime, m_endTime, m_lastCheckpointTime;
3495
3496 PerformanceTracker(void);
3497
3498 friend class el::PerformanceTrackingData;
3499 friend class base::DefaultPerformanceTrackingCallback;
3500
3501 const inline base::type::string_t getFormattedTimeTaken() const {
3502 return getFormattedTimeTaken(m_startTime);
3503 }
3504
3505 const base::type::string_t getFormattedTimeTaken(struct timeval startTime) const;
3506

3511class DefaultPerformanceTrackingCallback : public PerformanceTrackingCallback {
3512 protected:
3513 void handle(const PerformanceTrackingData* data) {
3514 m_data = data;
3515 base::type::stringstream_t ss;
3516 if (m_data->dataType() == PerformanceTrackingData::DataType::Complete) {
3517 ss << ELPP_LITERAL("Executed [") << m_data->blockName()->c_str() << ELPP_LITERAL("] in [") <<
3518 *m_data->formattedTimeTaken() << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3519 } else {
3520 ss << ELPP_LITERAL("Performance checkpoint");
3521 if (!m_data->checkpointId().empty()) {
3522 ss << ELPP_LITERAL(" [") << m_data->checkpointId().c_str() << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3523 }
3524 ss << ELPP_LITERAL(" for block [") << m_data->blockName()->c_str() << ELPP_LITERAL("] : [") <<
3525 *m_data->performanceTracker();
3526 if (!ELPP->hasFlag(LoggingFlag::DisablePerformanceTrackingCheckpointComparison)
3527 && m_data->performanceTracker()->m_hasChecked) {
3528 ss << ELPP_LITERAL(" ([") << *m_data->formattedTimeTaken() << ELPP_LITERAL("] from ");
3529 if (m_data->performanceTracker()->m_lastCheckpointId.empty()) {
3530 ss << ELPP_LITERAL("last checkpoint");
3531 } else {
3532 ss << ELPP_LITERAL("checkpoint '") << m_data->performanceTracker()->m_lastCheckpointId.c_str() << ELPP_LITERAL("'");
3533 }
3534 ss << ELPP_LITERAL(")]");
3535 } else {
3536 ss << ELPP_LITERAL("]");
3537 }
3538 }
3539 el::base::Writer(m_data->performanceTracker()->level(), m_data->file(), m_data->line(), m_data->func()).construct(1,
3540 m_data->loggerId().c_str()) << ss.str();
3541 }
3542 private:
3543 const PerformanceTrackingData* m_data;
3544};
3545} // namespace base

3565#if defined(ELPP_FEATURE_ALL) || defined(ELPP_FEATURE_CRASH_LOG)
3566class StackTrace : base::NoCopy {
3567 public:
3568 static const unsigned int kMaxStack = 64;
3569 static const unsigned int kStackStart = 2; // We want to skip c'tor and StackTrace::generateNew()
3570 class StackTraceEntry {
3571 public:
3572 StackTraceEntry(std::size_t index, const std::string& loc, const std::string& demang, const std::string& hex,
3573 const std::string& addr);
3574 StackTraceEntry(std::size_t index, const std::string& loc) :
3575 m_index(index),
3576 m_location(loc) {
3577 }
3578 std::size_t m_index;
3579 std::string m_location;
3580 std::string m_demangled;
3581 std::string m_hex;
3582 std::string m_addr;
3583 friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& ss, const StackTraceEntry& si);
3584
3585 private:
3586 StackTraceEntry(void);
3587 };
3588
3589 StackTrace(void) {
3590 generateNew();
3591 }
3592
3593 virtual ~StackTrace(void) {
3594 }
3595
3596 inline std::vector<StackTraceEntry>& getLatestStack(void) {
3597 return m_stack;
3598 }
3599
3600 friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const StackTrace& st);
3601
3602 private:
3603 std::vector<StackTraceEntry> m_stack;
3604
3605 void generateNew(void);
3606};
3607/// @brief Handles unexpected crashes
3608class CrashHandler : base::NoCopy {
3609 public:
3610 typedef void (*Handler)(int);
3611
3612 explicit CrashHandler(bool useDefault);
3613 explicit CrashHandler(const Handler& cHandler) {
3614 setHandler(cHandler);
3615 }
3616 void setHandler(const Handler& cHandler);
3617
3618 private:
3619 Handler m_handler;
3620};
3621#else
3622class CrashHandler {
3623 public:
3624 explicit CrashHandler(bool) {}
3625};
3626#endif // defined(ELPP_FEATURE_ALL) || defined(ELPP_FEATURE_CRASH_LOG)
3627} // namespace debug
3628} // namespace base

3632/// @brief Initializes syslog with process ID, options and facility. calls closelog() on d'tor
3633class SysLogInitializer {
3634 public:
3635 SysLogInitializer(const char* processIdent, int options = 0, int facility = 0) {
3636#if defined(ELPP_SYSLOG)
3637 (void)base::consts::kSysLogLoggerId;
3638 openlog(processIdent, options, facility);
3639#else
3640 ELPP_UNUSED(processIdent);
3641 ELPP_UNUSED(options);
3642 ELPP_UNUSED(facility);
3643#endif // defined(ELPP_SYSLOG)
3644 }
3645 virtual ~SysLogInitializer(void) {
3646#if defined(ELPP_SYSLOG)
3647 closelog();
3648#endif // defined(ELPP_SYSLOG)
3649 }
3650};
